{"id":31957,"date":"2022-03-03T13:54:48","date_gmt":"2022-03-03T21:54:48","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/?p=31957"},"modified":"2022-05-03T12:32:37","modified_gmt":"2022-05-03T19:32:37","slug":"bus-access","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/sw\/embedded\/opnpool-design\/bus-access-31957","title":{"rendered":"RS-485 bus"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>\r\n    The pool controller uses a &#8220;RS-485&#8221; bus to communicate with devices such as the pump and chlorinator. This is an industry standard two-wire bus with differential signaling. Devices are daisy-chained with 120 \u03a9 termination resistors on both ends to limit reflections.\r\n<\/p>\r\n<p>\r\n    By snooping the traffic on this bus, we can learn about the status of the controller. We can also observe commands that the controller sends to the devices and the subsequent responses that it receives.\r\n\r\n    <div class=\"flex-container tight\">\r\n        <figure>\r\n            <a href=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-ouside-scaled.jpg\"><img  title=\"\" src=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-ouside-982x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-31861\" srcset=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-ouside-982x1024.jpg 982w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-ouside-383x400.jpg 383w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-ouside-768x801.jpg 768w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-ouside-1472x1536.jpg 1472w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-ouside-1963x2048.jpg 1963w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 706px) 89vw, (max-width: 767px) 82vw, 740px\" \/><\/a>\r\n            <figcaption>\r\n                Opening the pool controller with a Phillips-head screwdriver\r\n            <\/figcaption>\r\n        <\/figure>\r\n    <\/div>\r\n<\/p>\r\n\r\n<h2>\r\n    Inside the controller\r\n<\/h2>\r\n<p>\r\n    The easiest place to access the bus is from the inside of the pool controller. \r\n<\/p>\r\n<p>\r\n    <div class=\"flex-container tight\">\r\n        <p class=\"important-note\" style=\"width: 80%;\">\r\n            <span class=\"icon\" style=\"font-size: 2rem;\">\u26a0<\/span>\r\n            THIS PROJECT IS OFFERED AS IS. IF YOU USE IT YOU ASSUME ALL RISKS. NO WARRENTIES. PROCEED AT YOUR OWN RISK! Always make sure to at the very least turn off the power while working on your pool equipment. Work carefully, THERE IS ALWAYS A RISK OF BREAKING YOUR POOL EQUIPMENT.\r\n        <\/p>\r\n    <\/div>\r\n<\/p>\r\n<p>\r\n    That being said, the RS-485 header can be found on the back of the control board. There are most likely wires already connected that go to devices such as the pump and chlorinator.\r\n\r\n    <div class=\"flex-container tight\">\r\n        <figure>\r\n            <a href=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-2.jpg\"><img src=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-2-1024x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-31859\" srcset=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-2-1024x1024.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-2-400x400.jpg 400w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-2-200x200.jpg 200w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-2-768x768.jpg 768w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-2-1536x1536.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-2-2048x2048.jpg 2048w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-2-100x100.jpg 100w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 706px) 89vw, (max-width: 767px) 82vw, 740px\" \/><\/a>\r\n            <figcaption>\r\n                Inside of controller\r\n            <\/figcaption>\r\n        <\/figure>\r\n        <figure>\r\n            <a href=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-connector-scaled.jpg\"><img src=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-connector-1024x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-31860\" srcset=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-connector-1024x1024.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-connector-400x400.jpg 400w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-connector-200x200.jpg 200w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-connector-768x768.jpg 768w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-connector-1536x1536.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-connector-2048x2048.jpg 2048w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/Pentair-ctrl-inside-connector-100x100.jpg 100w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 706px) 89vw, (max-width: 767px) 82vw, 740px\" \/><\/a>\r\n            <figcaption>\r\n                Inside of controller with the connector removed\r\n            <\/figcaption>\r\n        <\/figure>\r\n    <\/div>\r\n<\/p>\r\n<p>\r\n    To minimize electromagnetic interference, use two twisted pairs from something like a CAT-5e cable to connect the <code>A<\/code>\/<code>B<\/code> pair and the <code>+15V<\/code>\/<code>GND<\/code> power pair to the interface as shown in the table below. To minimize the risk of shorting the power, you probably don&#8217;t want to connect the power signal just yet.\r\n\r\n    <div>\r\n        <div class=\"flow-container\">\r\n            <table class=\"connections\">\r\n                <tr>\r\n                    <th colspan=\"2\" class=\"borderright\">Controller<\/th>\r\n                    <th colspan=\"2\">RS-485<\/th>\r\n                    <th>Cat5<\/th>\r\n                <\/tr>\r\n                <tr>\r\n                    <th>Com Port<\/th>\r\n                    <th>Name<\/th>\r\n                    <th>Name<\/th>\r\n                    <th>Idle state<\/th>\r\n                    <th>Wire Pair<\/th>\r\n                <\/tr>\r\n                <tr>\r\n                    <td>Green<\/td>\r\n                    <td><code>-DATA<\/code><\/td>\r\n                    <td><code>A<\/code><\/td>\r\n                    <td>negative<\/td>\r\n                    <td>pair 1<\/td>\r\n                <\/tr>\r\n                <tr>\r\n                    <td>Yellow<\/td>\r\n                    <td><code>+DATA<\/code><\/td>\r\n                    <td><code>B<\/code><\/td>\r\n                    <td>positive<\/td>\r\n                    <td>pair 1<\/td>\r\n                <\/tr>\r\n                <tr>\r\n                    <td>Red<\/td>\r\n                    <td><code>+15 V<\/code><\/td>\r\n                    <td><\/td>\r\n                    <td>n\/a<\/td>\r\n                    <td>pair 2<\/td>\r\n                <\/tr>\r\n                <tr>\r\n                    <td>Black<\/td>\r\n                    <td><code>GND<\/code><\/td>\r\n                    <td><\/td>\r\n                    <td>n\/a<\/td>\r\n                    <td>pair 2<\/td>\r\n                <\/tr>\r\n            <\/table>\r\n        <\/div>\r\n    <\/div>\r\n<\/p>\r\n\r\n<h2>\r\n    RS-485 connection\r\n<\/h2>\r\n<p>\r\n    With our cable connected, we can examine the signals. The shortest pulse length is about 104 \u00b5sec. From this, the data rate follows as 1\/0.000104 = 9600 baud. The exact flavor of the data bus is shown below.\r\n    <div class=\"flow-container tight\">\r\n        <table class=\"connections\">\r\n            <tr>\r\n                <th>Name<\/th>\r\n                <th>Value<\/th>\r\n            <\/tr>\r\n            <tr>\r\n                <td>baud rate<\/td>\r\n                <td>9600<\/td>\r\n            <\/tr>\r\n            <tr>\r\n                <td>data bits<\/td>\r\n                <td>8<\/td>\r\n            <\/tr>\r\n            <tr>\r\n                <td>parity<\/td>\r\n                <td>none<\/td>\r\n            <\/tr>\r\n            <tr>\r\n                <td>stop bits<\/td>\r\n                <td>1<\/td>\r\n            <\/tr>\r\n        <\/table>\r\n    <\/div>\r\n<\/p>\r\n<p>\r\n    Such a low data rate implies that we don&#8217;t have to be very concerned about daisy-chaining the devices. In other words, it is OK to just wiretap the signal on the controller.\r\n\r\n    <div class=\"flex-container tight\">\r\n        <figure>\r\n            <a href=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/opnpool-rs485-bitwidth-104usec.png\"><img src=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/opnpool-rs485-bitwidth-104usec.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"320\" class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-32111\" \/><\/a>\r\n            <figcaption>\r\n                1 bit takes &#038;thickapprox;104 \u00b5sec \r\n            <\/figcaption>\r\n        <\/figure>\r\n        <figure>\r\n            <a href=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/opnpool-rs485-breakout.png\"><img src=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/opnpool-rs485-breakout.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"320\" class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-32110\" srcset=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/opnpool-rs485-breakout.png 887w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/opnpool-rs485-breakout-400x283.png 400w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/opnpool-rs485-breakout-768x544.png 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 706px) 89vw, (max-width: 767px) 82vw, 740px\" \/><\/a>\r\n            <figcaption>\r\n                <a href=\"https:\/\/www.aliexpress.com\/item\/4001028673092.html\">RS-485 transceiver breakout<\/a>\r\n            <\/figcaption>\r\n        <\/figure>\r\n    <\/div>\r\n<\/p>\r\n<p>\r\n    When we connect the differential signal to a RS-485 transceiver such as the MAX485, we get regular TTL levels.\r\n\r\n    <div class=\"flex-container tight\">\r\n        <figure>\r\n            <a href=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/opnpool-rs485-one-message.png\"><img src=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/opnpool-rs485-one-message.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"320\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-32109\" \/><\/a>\r\n            <figcaption>\r\n                Single message\r\n            <\/figcaption>\r\n        <\/figure>\r\n        <figure>\r\n            <a href=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/opnpool-rs485-msg-repeats.png\"><img src=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/opnpool-rs485-msg-repeats.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"320\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-32112\" \/><\/a>\r\n            <figcaption>\r\n                Messages repeat every 2 sec\r\n            <\/figcaption>\r\n        <\/figure>\r\n    <\/div>\r\n<\/p>\r\n\r\n<h2>\r\n    TTL to CMOS signals\r\n<\/h2>\r\n<p>\r\n    The microcontrollers that we consider use CMOS voltages (3.3 V). For the prototypes, we used an existing breakout board, but replaced the MAX485 with a MAX3485 chip. While we&#8217;re at it, we&#8217;ll also remove the 10 k\u03a9 CMOS pullup resistors (<code>R1<\/code> &#8211; <code>R4<\/code>), but leave the RS-485 bias and bus termination resistors.\r\n\r\n    <div class=\"flex-container tight\">\r\n        <figure>\r\n            <a href=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/opnpool-rs485-breakout-schematic.png\"><img src=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/opnpool-rs485-breakout-schematic.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"320\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-32256\" srcset=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/opnpool-rs485-breakout-schematic.png 536w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/opnpool-rs485-breakout-schematic-400x277.png 400w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 536px) 100vw, 536px\" \/><\/a>\r\n            <figcaption>\r\n                Breakout schematic<br \/>Source: <a href=\"https:\/\/arduinoinfo.mywikis.net\/wiki\/RS485-Modules\">yourduino.com<\/a>\r\n            <\/figcaption>\r\n        <\/figure>\r\n        <figure>\r\n            <a href=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/RS485-with-new-3V3-part-scaled.jpg\"><img src=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/RS485-with-new-3V3-part-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"320\" class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-31865\" srcset=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/RS485-with-new-3V3-part-1024x683.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/RS485-with-new-3V3-part-400x267.jpg 400w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/RS485-with-new-3V3-part-768x512.jpg 768w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/RS485-with-new-3V3-part-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/wp-content\/uploads\/RS485-with-new-3V3-part-2048x1365.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 706px) 89vw, (max-width: 767px) 82vw, 740px\" \/><\/a>\r\n            <figcaption>\r\n                RS485 with new 3.3V part\r\n            <\/figcaption>\r\n        <\/figure>\r\n    <\/div>\r\n<\/p>\r\n<p>\r\n    <div class=\"continue-container no-print\">\r\n        <div class=\"continue-content\">\r\n            <div class=\"continue-text\">\r\n                Knowing about the interface and baud rate, we can move on to building a system that interprets the proprietary message protocol. Continue reading to learn about the <a href=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/sw\/embedded\/opnpool-design\/hardware-3-31959\">hardware design<\/a>.\r\n            <\/div>\r\n        <\/div>\r\n    <\/div>    \r\n<\/p>\r\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"Describes the RS-485 bus that the pool controller uses to communicate with devices such as the pump and chlorinator.","protected":false},"author":41,"featured_media":32091,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"inline_featured_image":false,"_mi_skip_tracking":false},"categories":[434],"tags":[463,455,461,460],"yoast_head":"<!-- This site is o